        {
          "username": "Nancy C",
          "rating": 1,
          "contributor_id": "101857969406627228053",
          "user_review_count": 27,
          "user_photo_count": 14,
          "user_thumbnail": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/ACg8ocLEL4V8AmSmErdfXgpOvKFaO10vBoYaDK1khxZ1XnOMhj5iPc8=s120-c-rp-mo-ba12-br100",
          "description": "Dr Leone is rude and unprofessional. I\u2019ve been a patient since 2021 but will be switching practices because of her. While most of the staff are respectful and professional, and I am sad to leave a place I\u2019ve grow accustomed to over the years, I refuse to support Dr Leone given her negligent behavior.\n\nShe cut my dental exam short because SHE was delayed and couldn\u2019t manage her schedule, denied my historical issues with sensitivity, and talked down to me by invalidating my experience when other doctors have told me that teeth whitening can permanently impact your teeth.\n\nMy appointment was at 11:00am. Jose was great, and completed the cleaning around 11:40am. I waited 30 minutes for Dr Leone, who came in around 12:15pm.\n\nWhen she finally arrived, I mentioned sensitivity and requested some solutions such as prescription fluoride (based on my own research). She said there was no record of sensitivity in my files, and I stated I was shocked as I mention it every time I\u2019m there during the cleaning and some of the hygienists even have used numbing cream. I stated it began after I used whitening strips 15 years ago and my teeth never felt the same since then. She talked down to me and refused to listen. She denied this one time use would create sensitivity for years so I asked her what would cause it then? She didn\u2019t respond. Other dentists at her practice have stated that whitening can permanently alter teeth so was she calling us all liars?\n\nHer assistant was thoughtful and after noticing Dr Leone\u2019s lack of response, the assistant asked if I experienced sensitivity on the left side of my teeth as she had looked at my xrays and could see some gum recession. I told her yes I have sensitivity in the back of my teeth.\n\nSince Dr Leone didn\u2019t respond, I asked for prescription fluoride. She stated she was very busy and had other patients waiting, so she would not send the prescription until EOD or even the next day.\n\nShe proceeded to spend less than a minute examining my teeth. I only felt my bottom teeth being checked with the tool so I asked whether the top teeth had been examined as I noticed on the scans that there were stains on one tooth and I wanted to confirm that there were no cavities as previous dentists at her practice had suggested we keep an eye on it.\n\nSince my pharmacy was only a few blocks away, I asked again after the exam in hopes it could be done before I left, but she stated \u201cI have three other patients waiting and cant sit in front of a computer right now\u201d and left abruptly.\n\nAfter Dr Leon left, the assistant tried to do some damage control and took time to explain the x-ray/scans to me, including that the areas noted appeared to be stains rather than cavities.\n\nMy appt was at 11am. If you are 3 patients behind by that time, don\u2019t take it out on your patients and cut corners. You cannot skip my oral exam because you\u2019re late. You should schedule fewer people or hire more staff instead of cutting corners and not conducting a through oral exam.\n\nThe prescription was ultimately not provided during the visit nor EOD and I had to follow up with staff the next day via email to request the prescription.",
          "link": "https://www.google.com/maps/reviews/data=!4m8!14m7!1m6!2m5!1sCi9DQUlRQUNvZENodHljRjlvT2pOS1ltOWtXbFZGU2t0UE1VWnZUVTV3V0hwRGEwRRAB!2m1!1s0x0:0x75ffb990d55e0408!3m1!1s2@1:CAIQACodChtycF9oOjNKYm9kWlVFSktPMUZvTU5wWHpDa0E%7C%7C?hl=en",
